title: Made RegressionStrategy.scala and Indicators more modular
body:
Our code works and runs to create a graph for both ShiftsIndicator and RSIIndicator. Developer should be able to extend BaseIndicator to implement new feature, though there are still some issues remaining. The major ones are:

FBIC-3 Make params to RSIIndicator a case class
FBIC-9 metricsParams are always from emptyStrategy, should be from RegressionStrategy
FBIC-11 fix the difference in graphs of ShiftsIndicator, apparently, the coefficient vector comes out different
FBIC-16 abstract the max period of indicators -> firstIdx = getMaxOffSet() + 3 in createModel
FBIC-19 shouldn't need to loop through indicators, use mapping function
FBIC-22 Document RegressionStrategy
FBIC-26 Implement a new indicator to see how well our class works

We still have some work to do so we don't expect this pull request to be accepted. Hoping this serves as a brief code review. Please comment on any issue you can and looking forward to what you have to say!

title: Experimental BulkCsvUploader
body:
Hi guys,

I faced on the last days the slow upload data problem when try to send my data to PredictionIO server and after some googling I found in the user forum discussions the experimental bulk upload tool. This was the path to solve this problem. :)

I'm starting with Recommendations, Mahout, PredictionIO and I have a little experience in Java/Scala.

Thinking about how to make this upload more easy, I implemented a extended version of the original bulkUploader to work with CSV files. The main idea is enable the user to upload items, users and U2Iactions in distinct files to specific Apps.

I'm not implemented the unit tests because not have any to the original toolsBulkUpload. I'm imagining that is because a experimental stuff.

In the tests, under the Amazon MarketPlace pre-built PredictionIO machine with 8GB of memory, I uploaded 3000000 u2iactions in 7,8 minutes.

I hope this help a little.

title: Trending Item Recommendation
body:
This pull request introduces time-series trending analysis as an item recommendation engine. As opposed to the one currently in the trending_algo branch, this one does a series of regressions and has an optional filters to smooth the data. The minimum number of parameters are exposed to the end user because we assume they don't have extensive knowledge about time series analysis (although we can change that later).
As it sits right now, the Trending.scala test files have yet to be written, but should be done soon by Haoyuan.
